PREAMBLE

This Aethelgrad Reciprocal Public Code Covenant (the "Covenant") is a legal agreement between Aethelgrad Studio ("Licensor") and any person or entity that downloads, clones, installs, executes, or distributes the Work ("Recipient"). The Licensor believes in open collaboration but reserves absolute control over its intellectual property. This Covenant grants broad open source freedoms while retaining a unilateral termination right (the "red button") and strict trademark protections.

By obtaining a copy of the Work, the Recipient agrees to be bound by the terms of this Covenant.
ARTICLE 1: DEFINITIONS

1.1 "Work" means the software source code, object code, documentation, configuration files, build scripts, metadata, visual design elements, and any associated materials made available by the Licensor in any repository referencing this Covenant, together with all updates and successor versions.

1.2 "Recipient" means any individual or legal entity that downloads, clones, installs, executes, distributes, or otherwise obtains a copy of the Work.

1.3 "Derivative Work" means any work based upon or derived from the Work, including modifications, translations, ports, adaptations, or any other form in which the Work may be recast, transformed, or adapted.

1.4 "Contribution" means any code, documentation, or other material intentionally submitted to the Licensor for inclusion in the Work.

1.5 "Licensor" means Aethelgrad Studio, its successors, and assigns.

1.6 "Covenant" means this instrument, including all articles and any future amendments published by the Licensor.

1.7 The singular includes the plural, and "including" means "including without limitation".
ARTICLE 2: COPYRIGHT LICENSE – OPEN SOURCE GRANT

2.1 Scope of Grant. Subject to the terms of this Covenant (including the revocation power in Article 5 and the trademark restrictions in Article 4), the Licensor hereby grants to each Recipient a worldwide, non-exclusive, royalty-free, non-transferable copyright license to:

    (a) reproduce, copy, and distribute the Work, in whole or in part, in Source or Object form;

    (b) prepare, use, and distribute Derivative Works of the Work;

    (c) publicly display, publicly perform, and otherwise use the Work; and

    (d) sublicense any of the foregoing rights to third parties, provided that any sublicense includes a copy of this Covenant and notice that all permissions are revocable.

2.2 Commercial Use Permitted. Commercial use, including but not limited to selling copies, incorporating the Work into paid products or services, and using the Work in revenue‑generating activities, is expressly permitted under this license. However, the Licensor reserves the right to invoke Article 6 (Financial Clawback) at any time.

2.3 Patent License. Each Contributor grants each Recipient a worldwide, non‑exclusive, royalty‑free patent license to make, use, sell, offer for sale, and import the Work, limited to patent claims necessarily infringed by that Contributor's Contribution(s).

2.4 No Implied Licenses. No rights are granted by implication, estoppel, or otherwise beyond those expressly stated in this Covenant.
ARTICLE 3: CONDITIONS AND LIMITATIONS

3.1 Preservation of Notices. Any distribution of the Work or Derivative Work must retain all copyright, patent, trademark, and attribution notices from the original Work.

3.2 No Use of Licensor's Trademarks. Recipient may not use any trademark, service mark, trade name, logo, or brand identifier of the Licensor, including but not limited to "Aethelgrad", "Aethelgrad Studio", "AethelLib", and any confusingly similar variants, without the Licensor's express written permission. This prohibition applies to:

    (a) naming any Derivative Work, fork, repository, or package;

    (b) using the marks in advertising, product packaging, or promotional materials;

    (c) any use likely to cause confusion about origin, endorsement, or affiliation.

3.3 No Registry Squatting. Recipient may not publish, upload, or register any software package, library, or module bearing a name that includes or is confusingly similar to the Licensor's marks to any package registry, including but not limited to npm, crates.io, PyPI, Maven Central, RubyGems, Packagist, NuGet, Conda, Homebrew, Docker Hub, or any analogous registry.

3.4 No Modification of This Covenant. Recipient may not alter, amend, or supplement the terms of this Covenant with respect to the Work. Any purported modification is void.
ARTICLE 4: CONTRIBUTION ASSIGNMENT

4.1 Irrevocable Assignment. Any Contribution intentionally submitted to the Licensor is hereby irrevocably assigned to the Licensor, including all copyright, patent, trademark, trade secret, and any other intellectual property rights therein. The Contributor waives any moral rights to the extent permitted by law.

4.2 No Obligation to Use. The Licensor may accept, reject, modify, or disregard any Contribution without any duty to credit or compensate the Contributor.

4.3 No Withdrawal. Once submitted, a Contribution may not be revoked or reclaimed.
ARTICLE 5: UNILATERAL REVOCATION (THE "RED BUTTON")

5.1 Absolute Revocation Power. The Licensor retains the absolute, unilateral, and discretionary right to revoke the licenses granted under Article 2 with respect to any specific Recipient, any category of Recipients, or all Recipients collectively. Revocation may be exercised for any reason, for no reason, for arbitrary reasons, or for reasons based on mistaken facts.

5.2 Manner of Revocation. The Licensor may effect revocation by:

    (a) sending written notice to the Recipient (including electronic mail);

    (b) public announcement in the repository associated with the Work; or

    (c) any other means reasonably calculated to provide notice.

Revocation becomes effective upon the Recipient's receipt of notice or fifteen (15) days after public posting, whichever is earlier.

5.3 Prospective Only. Revocation applies prospectively only. Uses of the Work that occurred before the effective date of revocation remain licensed under the terms then in effect. The Licensor does not claim retroactive revocation.

5.4 Consequences of Revocation. Upon revocation, the Recipient must immediately cease all distribution, modification, and use of the Work, and destroy all copies in its possession, custody, or control.

5.5 Fork and Derivative Termination. Revocation applies to any Derivative Work, fork, or adaptation controlled by the Recipient.
ARTICLE 6: FINANCIAL CLAWBACK

6.1 Commercial Utilization Review. Although commercial use is permitted, the Licensor may, in its sole discretion, determine that a Recipient's commercial use is excessive, exploitative, or detrimental to the Licensor's legitimate interests. Factors may include revenue scale, market impact, or failure to provide attribution.

6.2 Licensor's Election. Upon such determination, the Licensor may elect to:

    (a) Demand a Reasonable Fee. Propose a royalty or flat license fee. The Recipient shall have thirty (30) days to accept in writing and pay the demanded amount. If the Recipient fails to do so, the license is automatically revoked under Article 5.

    (b) Immediate Revocation. Revoke the Recipient's license without offering a fee option.

6.3 Audit Right. Upon reasonable suspicion of material commercial use, the Licensor may demand a complete accounting of revenues attributable to the Work. The Recipient shall provide such accounting within thirty (30) days, certified under penalty of perjury. Failure to provide an accounting shall entitle the Licensor to presume statutory damages of no less than USD $50,000.

6.4 No Waiver. The Licensor's failure to exercise clawback against any Recipient does not waive its right to do so against the same or any other Recipient later.
ARTICLE 7: DISCLAIMER OF WARRANTIES

THE WORK IS PROVIDED "AS IS" AND "AS AVAILABLE", WITHOUT WARRANTIES OF ANY KIND, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, INCLUDING BUT NOT LIMITED TO WARRANTIES OF MERCHANTABILITY, FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE, TITLE, NON‑INFRINGEMENT, OR ACCURACY. THE LICENSOR DOES NOT WARRANT THAT THE WORK WILL BE UNINTERRUPTED, SECURE, OR ERROR‑FREE.
ARTICLE 8: LIMITATION OF LIABILITY

IN NO EVENT SHALL THE LICENSOR BE LIABLE FOR ANY DIRECT, INDIRECT, INCIDENTAL, SPECIAL, CONSEQUENTIAL, OR PUNITIVE DAMAGES, INCLUDING LOSS OF PROFITS, GOODWILL, USE, OR DATA, ARISING OUT OF OR RELATING TO THIS COVENANT OR THE WORK, EVEN IF ADVISED OF THE POSSIBILITY OF SUCH DAMAGES.
ARTICLE 9: INDEMNIFICATION

The Recipient shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Licensor from any claims, damages, or expenses (including reasonable attorneys' fees) arising from:

    (a) the Recipient's use or distribution of the Work;

    (b) any Derivative Work created by the Recipient;

    (c) any violation of this Covenant.

ARTICLE 10: MODIFICATION OF COVENANT

10.1 Unilateral Amendment. The Licensor may modify this Covenant at any time by publishing an updated version in the repository associated with the Work.

10.2 Notice and Acceptance. The Licensor will provide notice of material changes by updating the "Effective Date" and posting a summary. Continued use of the Work more than thirty (30) days after such notice constitutes acceptance of the amended terms.

10.3 No Right to Notice. Recipients are responsible for periodically reviewing this Covenant. The Licensor is not required to provide individual notice.
ARTICLE 11: SEVERABILITY

If any provision of this Covenant is held unenforceable, the remainder shall continue in full force, and the unenforceable provision shall be reformed to the minimum extent necessary to make it enforceable.
ARTICLE 12: ACCEPTANCE OF TERMS

12.1 Manifestation of Assent. By downloading, cloning, installing, executing, or distributing the Work, the Recipient affirmatively agrees to be bound by all terms of this Covenant.

12.2 No Browsewrap. Mere viewing of the Work in a web browser without obtaining a copy does not constitute acceptance. Acceptance occurs only when the Recipient takes an affirmative step to acquire or use the Work.

12.3 Termination for Non‑Acceptance. If the Recipient does not agree to any term of this Covenant, it must not download, install, or use the Work, and must destroy any copies already obtained.
ARTICLE 13: GOVERNING LAW AND JURISDICTION

13.1 Governing Law. This Covenant shall be governed by the laws of the jurisdiction where the Licensor resides at the time of enforcement, without regard to conflict of laws principles. The Licensor may elect to apply the laws of any jurisdiction where the Recipient resides or where infringement occurred.

13.2 Exclusive Jurisdiction. Any dispute arising under this Covenant shall be resolved exclusively in the courts of the jurisdiction selected by the Licensor. The Recipient irrevocably submits to personal jurisdiction there and waives any objection based on venue or forum non conveniens.

13.3 Service of Process. The Recipient agrees that service of process may be effected by electronic mail to any address associated with the Recipient or by public notification in the Work's repository.
ARTICLE 14: ENTIRE AGREEMENT

This Covenant constitutes the entire agreement between the Licensor and the Recipient concerning the Work. It supersedes all prior communications, representations, or agreements, whether written or oral. The Recipient acknowledges that it has not relied on any representation not expressly set forth herein.
